title: Capacitive sensor holder for Wilson RepRap

description.text:
I took the idea of design from nhambayi and adapted it for the capacitive sensor. I made the embedded nut for easy adjustment of the sensor height.
LJC18A3-B-Z/BY is the sensor we use.
I put the support material for friendly printing of the model. It is easy removable with a knife.
you can easily attach the holder to your cold end carriage by enlarging the bolts and putting the second nut to each one. don't forget to put washers.

I also attached the .ipt file in case you want to upgrade something.

I recommend to print the model with the sensor hole attached to bed, so that you get perfect cylinder for the sensor. And the support material will help to close the bridge.

Feel free to post your makes and remixes!

title: Extended Greg's extruder for Reprap Samuel

description.text: My modified Greg's extruder for the RepRap Samuel. I designed this for my second printer because I couldn't find a geared extruder for my Samuel. This model keeps the motor out of the way and above the X-Axis rods. Also, For this printer I chose the Prometheus hotend which mount is very similar to a J-head hotend but still a bit different, So I incorporated a hotend clamp by slipstream into the extruder to allow for slight differences in hotend mounts. I also included supports inside the file so it can be printed without any support settings inside your slicer. For use with standard 1/5 gears.

I recently bought one of those cheap chinese component testers on ebay, and designed a case for it.
My goals were to keep it as small as possible, while still keeping enough space to add three 2mm Connectors in order to use the tester with external cables.

It should fit three of those (I have not ordered and tried them yet!): http://www.reichelt.at/Buchsen/MBI-1-AU-SW/3/index.html?ACTION=3&GROUPID=5621&ARTICLE=128912&OFFSET=16&WKID=0&

The 9V battery snaps in place and sits firmly, without moving even a bit. The whole case can be used without any screws, but I would recommend mounting the PCB with at least one screw.

The screen is lowered a bit into the case in order to protect it from scratches and other mechanical damages.

Files:
lcr_top - lid of the case
lcr_bottom - bottom of the case, with three holes for the three 2mm connectors
lcr_bottom_noholes - bottom without holes for connectors

comments.text:
Hi ya, No problem, I got a bit busy today too.
First of all, the support. You can enable/disable it from the Slic3r Settings. Printer Settings > Support Material, tick or untick the Generate Support Material check box.
Now I've seen the model, I can see that the burns and droops in the first 2 pictures are where there is overhang. Assuming that your thumb is where the part was sitting on the bed? This is where the layer is over hanging the previous layer and not sticking to it properly, therefore drooping down. This can be helped by reducing the hotend temp still further, assuming you can do this without going too low. Trial and error again I'm afraid. The burning is still making me think that the temp is a little too high. It could also be that the filament is crap. Do you have another roll you can try?
In the second and third pictures. The random mess that is in the square hole looks like support material that has been printed too hot and has simply collapsed. Again maybe down to the hotend temp being too high. Since the roof of the hole looks quite good, I doubt you will need support there anyway.
In the third picture, I see a lot of stringing. This is material that seeps from the nozzle as in moves between printing moves. The usual causes for this are; hotend temp too high, retraction distance too small/slow, movement speed (non-printing moves) too slow.
Clearly the one common factor here points to the hotend temp being too high for the filament. Check the requirements of the filament from the manufacturers website and run some test prints. Here's an overhang test model to save you some time and filament https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2298057
Lastly, here is a bridging test model if you want to check, if your temp is too high, it will show up by sagging when printing the first few layers of the bridge https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:113160
Add some pics of your testing so I can see if we are getting anywhere.
Almost forgot about the leaking. I think your hotend is almost a one-piece item, unlike the E3D v6 etc, so may not have any leakage.
Are you planning on fitting an E3D v6 to it?
Good luck
PS: Don't think you're a nuisance mate, I help because I'm happy to. I was a beginner once and got a LOT of help from others online. I'm more than happy to return the favour.

comments.text: Spike, unbelievably, I JUST saw the notification email from thingiverse amid the myriad other emails I received that day! I often run low on battery with this phone 3/4 way through the day and turn my battery save mode on. This turns off any apps that constantly update themselves via the network. In this case g-mail. I apologize for the delay man. Thanks for the test prints. I'm going to try them out this weekend, probably Saturday and get back to you with results. I did check the manufacturer's temp requirements and they're absurdly low for abs. They want 200-230 for the hot end (which seems reasonable) and 55-85 for the bed (which doesn't). I tried 85 for the bed and the material wouldn't stick, as expected. I lowered the hot end and got slightly better results, but whoever I print a curve or fillet from the bed up, that is when the filleted surface is parallel to the bed, it looks like absolute crap. comments.author: SpikeUK

comments.text:
Hey, no problem. I'm still here :-)
I look forward to your results.
The reason the filets, parallel with the bed, turn out so bad is simply due to overhang. The radius of the fillet dictates that the first layer of the fillet is flat to the bed, the second layer has to create the start of a very gentle curve therefore, it will be a very steep overhang so will print too far outside of the previous layer. As the print progresses to subsequent layers, the radius of the fillet means the layers become less steep so will print better as they don't print outside of the previous layer. You can reduce this effect 2 way, 1) reduce the layer height of the first few layers of the fillet, 2) Keep the fillets to a smaller radius.
An alternative to using a fillet, is to use a chamfer instead. This will use a 45 degree slope, which should be easy to print, rather than a radius.
Hope I've explained that clearly, if not, let me know and I'll have another go :-)

A popular video showed up on Youtube on how to make a 100W led flashlight. He uses a huge CPU cooler but I found that I could just use a small one and it won't get that warm.

So that's why I created this flashlight housing. The CPU cooler is press fitted. It latches on to the layers of the plastic so it stays put, but it isn't perfect. I'll try to run some tests to see how long it will work. Enjoy!

Materials used:
CPU cooler from AMD A4-3400 (I paid 10 euro's for it (Yes, that's including the CPU!))
(I believe all FM1 and maybe other AMD socket CPU coolers are identical)
100W LED (~4 USD)
LED Lens (~3.5 USD)
150W DC-DC Boost Converter (~3,5 USD)
Heatsink paste for mounting the LED to the cooler (~1 USD)
10K Ohm resistor for dimmer control 5x (~2.5 USD) (or any 10k pot with M7 screw)
Potentiometer cap x10 (~1.5 USD)
Switch 5x (~2 USD) (or any ~22mm switch)
Zippy Compact 2200mAh 3s LiPo (~12 USD)
LiPo battery monitor(~1.5 USD)(not sure if this will fit at all, I left it out)
And then two m3 screws for securing the boost converter, three m2 screws for the lids, some wires, a female XT60 connector and two ~11K resistors.

I didn't use the step-down regulator for the fan, I wired it directly to the input of the battery so it can be a bit loud. You can wire an additional potentiometer or a resistor (find out which value by using a potentiometer first and measure its resistance). A potentiometer works just as well since the fan is pretty much a resistance.

It's a tight fit

Update 6/25/15: I added a new deeper reel with a much greater line capacity. The name of the file is 'New Reel.stl'. The full plate of parts named 'Fishing Rod.stl' has had this new reel added to it, so by printing out the plate you can have both and choose one.

When you print it out, using a brim of 10mm or more is recommended to increase the contact area between the rod and the bed to prevent warping. The rod assembles very simply and easily. Slide the round spool into the spool holder on the main rod body. The crank then gets pushed through the rod and spool. Make sure that the hole in the crank and the hole in the spool align, as this is what you tie the fishing line through to keep it from slipping. You can make it for left or right handed, but once you press the crank in it is really hard to pull out. You may even need to pound the crank in with a mallet or other heavy object.

My entry for the #MakeItFloat challenge. I originally meant to make a floating raft with 8 floaters around a center base, but changed my mind quite quickly into another concept: a floating candle.

I decided to make a few calculations regarding the maximum weight/mass of the floater, and then predicting the amount of mass that the object could hold, and see how close to reality that prediction is.

From the calculations below, we predicted a maximum theoretical load of 125 g, though anything above 100 g would be more than enough to hold a meager candle.

From this point forward, there will be some simple physics for those interested.

What allows various objects to float in water is that the total density of the object is lower than that of the water. The word total there is important because even though cargo ships are made of some kind of metal, the air inside them has much lower density, allowing the ship to float.

The maximum cargo that the object can carry afloat is calculated as:
m = ρ * V

Where ρ is the density of the fluid (for water, it is 1 g/cm3) and V is the volume that was displaced.

Therefore, with a volume of around 150 cm3 (calculated through Fusion 360), the mass of water that is displaced is 150 grams.

With 10% infill, the floater has a total mass of around 25 g, meaning that, theoretically, we could support a maximum of 125 grams (let's say 100 g to be safe).
V1 and v3 - Print with 10% infill, and as much wall size as you want.

title: E3D Chimera Hotend Adaptor for CraftBot
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
I've decided to try the new E3D Chimera hotend on my CraftBot.

This is still work in progress, but so far test prints of sitting fox by PHYSICS_DUDE (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:166984) and Aria The Dragon by loubie (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:600550) seemed to print well.

Update 2017-01-26: I have changed to use Bart's custom E3D all metal hotend instead for quite some time. It works great. https://craftunique.com/forums/view-thread/1434

Please note that this is a work in progress.

This is an adaptor to hold an E3D Chimera hotend on a CraftBot 3D printer.

I have a Chimera dual hotend and also an E3D-V6 hotend. Since the heat sink of a Chimera hotend fits easier on the CraftBot, I have decided to try it on my CraftBot.

It's using only half the Chimera dual hotend. I'm hoping that I can use both on future CraftBot upgrade.

[Update: I have cut out the right corner of the adaptor so it doesn't get blocked by the fan screw hole. New R4 file uploaded. ]

Parts Needed:
1) Print out the STL file in ABS.
2) M6 nozzle throat.
http://www.ebay.com/itm/M6-x-26-5-Nozzle-Throat-for-makerbot-3D-Printer-Extruder-Hot-and-NEW-/261941957424?pt=LH_DefaultDomain_0&hash=item3cfcf51330
3) Short PTFE tube.

Instruction:
1) Print out the STL file in ABS.
2) Enlarge the thermistor hole in the Chimera heating block by drilling so it can accept stock CraftBot thermistor.
3) Cut the M6 nozzle throat in the section where there's no thread.
4) Heat up the nozzle throat. I heated the nozzle throat on my gas stove. Be careful, it is hot.
5) Slowly insert the nozzle throat (the cut end) into the printed adaptor (the left opening with the heat sink fin facing you). Make sure that it stands straight up. When it's good, let it cool.
6) Insert the PTFE tube into the (already assembled hotend) Chimera heat sink. Cut the PTFE tube with a sharp knife flush with the top of the heat sink.
7) Attach the adaptor (with nozzle throat already inserted) to the top of the heat sink. Screw in the 3 screws.
8) Insert the Chimera hotend into the CraftBot hotend holder.
9) Screw the nut on the M6 nozzle throat to hold the hotend. Don't tighten yet.
10) Place the stock CraftBot fans back and insert it between the hotend holder and the nozzle throat. Adjust the position to make sure that the hotend is sitting firmly, then tighten the M6 nut and also the the fan holder screws.
11) Connect the hotend heating cartridge and thermistor on the heat block.
12) Calibrate your heat bed platform.

Do a preliminary test print.

Congratulations! You're done!

Please feel free to provide your suggestions/feedbacks or feel free to mod it.

description.text: Plastic air rifle pellets

When I signed in to upload this project I searched "pellets" and came upon this one. http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:388339
There may be others.
I make no claim to be the first to do this. Since I have the project and photos all ready to go, I figure I'll post it anyway since my own experiences might add something to the idea.
..........

I've been playing with this pellet rifle (Daisy 880, .177 caliber) and wondered about printing pellets.
There are a few plastic pellets on the market, presumably for indoor target practice with low-power pistols. Others have metal inserts to make them more effective for hunting and plinking.

I printed a few. One thing was immediately clear. Printed plastic pellets are very high speed. They weigh next to nothing so this is understandable.

I tried different configurations...Straight cylinders, balls at the end of hollow cylinders, rounded cones, etc. but the standard, waisted pellets with a hollow skirt is the best so far.

They aren't very accurate. I tested a few indoors and would be happy to keep them in a 2 inch circle at about 10 yards. They have a terribly rough surface and you can expect large groups and some flyers.

This same pellet design is also the fastest. Surprisingly it broke the sound barrier (see photo) but I wasn't prepared for a sonic boom (probably a crack) and didn't hear one over the other noises. [Edit: The crack is definitely there.] Speed was measured at point blank range with a rifle. A light pellet will slow down much sooner than a heavier one.

[Moved back 8 feet (~2.5m) from the chronometer, FPS dropped to about 980, so it lost 200 feet per second (~17%) in just 8 feet. That's a terrible hit on speed.... but what's worse is it lost ~1/3 of its impact energy.]

At 10 yards it still hits very hard. They flatten out somewhat if the target is paper, like cardboard, and sometimes ricocheted all the way back to me. For my rifle at near maximum power, penetration was about 6 or 8 corrugated cardboard sheets (from standard shipping boxes) at about 8 yards.

They are delicate at the thin waist. Be careful when removing them from their rafts. Best to cut them free with a razor blade. Tried no raft but they have a small footprint and don't stick well.

A set of nine pellets took 24 minutes and used just 1.5 grams ABS with a raft, 0.15mm Z, slowest speed. Also used fan cooling. These are really tiny prints and when it comes to pellets, accuracy is everything. Give them all the help you can.

Metric version included.

This is a little fixture which clips onto the top of the SD2 frame, and holds a smooth 7.3 mm diameter rod just inside and above the Y-axis belt, keeping the wire bundle from hitting that belt when the extruder is on that side of the unit. I made the "Solidoodle extruder head wire bundle guide" by robbruton (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:51134), but couldn't get it to print as smoothly as I'd like, and within a couple of days I started seeing some of the black braid surrounding the wires rubbing off on the guide, so I just needed something smoother, and the aluminum rods fit the bill nicely.

To use the STL file without modification, you need a 7.3 mm diameter rod that's 235 mm long.  For some reason, the previous owner of my house left a bunch of them in one of the closets.  In case you don't have such a perfectly sized rod, I've included the Sketchup file so you can change the diameter of the rod it can hold.  
You print out two of the holders, and I suggest 100% infill, which in Slic3r resulted in them being completely solid.  Put them at opposite ends of the rod, install and watch as your Y-belt and extruder wire bundle live in harmony.

I really liked the Mobius mount that Dimon372 had published ( http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:665417 ) but found it broke a little too easy for me. I added about a mm each direction and some more mounting points and a bit more lens protection. I also integrated a bit of a tilt into the mount, around 10 degrees.

I was using the little rubber dampeners but they break too easy. Instead I printed a pad for the mount to sit on out of Ninjaflex with a bit of a void inside of it to help dampen the camera. So far it is working great.

As you can see, the overhangs weren't perfect for the tie-downs on the mobius. For what it is worth, these feel strong and do not seem like they will be the weak point on this print - I am guessing it will be the lack of 'top' coverage as that is a direct impact point.

EDIT 8/3/2015 - I have been using this mount for the last month or so and really like how it is working. I have shaved off a little bit of weight in the front of the wedge and reinforced the top band across the lens. This is V4 for me, I will leave the previous version up so both versions are available.

I am also just using a velcro strap to hold the Mobius in. It has worked very well and makes removing the Mobius quite easy.

title: Replicator Accessories - Fan Guard, Fume Extractor & Fan Draft Terminator
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
There are a few designs out there to keep the cooling fans from blowing air on your build platform (ABS Printing).  Thus, decreasing warping when printing without a raft and adding a noticeable increase in print adhesion. There are also some designs for ABS fume extraction, but most require an additional fan and move a ton of air, which contradicts the above.  
I decided to take the best ideas from a few and mesh them into one, using the existing Replicator fans.

This fits a Dual Extruder Replicator 1 diverts the air up away from the build platform and can be fitted with attachments.  The attachment posted can have active carbon added to reduce ABS fumes.  
All parts were designed on Google SketchUp, slip into place (no screws or glue), are meant to fit snug and can be readily replaced or upgraded.  
The .thing files attached are the way (orientation) I printed the .stl files on my Replicator.  Printed with MakerWare default medium profile settings (raft & support).  
Happy printing!  
Update: After some serious printing hours... zero abs fumes, consistent print temps and much better print adhesion vs. normal printing.  
Update: Some new pictures of how the active carbon was used, basically an active carbon sandwich.  Filter, carbon, filter.  New attachments in the works.  
Update: v4 has side covers that can be opened for cooling.  I found that opening the cover on the fan side that is printing (when using one extruder) works very well at both cooling and fume extraction. As the non-printing fan kicks off closer to build time and shuts off first after build completion.

A pirate ship, I told my 4yr daughter about the #MakeItFloat challenge. She said she wanted to get involved, but could we make a pirate ship. This is the current result.

I have printed the first prototype on an Up Plus, at 0.2mm layer depth and loose fill. The final boat weighs in at 50g, but will not float upright without some ballast. I managed to float 114g of Australian coins, but am in the process of improving the design to be able to hold more weight.

The hull prints pretty much without support, it only required support for the slide for the deck, and the holes for the railing to glue into. Choose which hull file you would like, Hull02nocham is the bare hull, whereas Hull03 is the hull with vertical barriers running the length of the ship. I hope this adds compartments for storing the coins more efficiently, and also so that the water has to flood each section before getting to the next.

Both the masts have holes in them for 'sewing' sails onto, however they did not turn out in the first prototype. The front spike is also not quite working as intended currently.

The masts require support as they print at 90degrees to upright. The deck requires support for the railing at the top, and surprisingly the wheel printed ok on my printer.

The railing should be printed upside down to avoid the need for support.

Designed in 123d Design.

title: Solidoodle Aluminium Bed Anti-Backlash/Wobble PLA Nut

description.text:
Following the theme that a taller nut on the bed->leadscrew interface will help reduce backlash and wobble, here is a PLA printed assembly for use with the new Aluminium Platforms from Solidoodle.  
On the platform you will find 4 screw holes surrounding the leadscrew nut. Tap these out to M4.  
Print the nut using PLA as ABS will flex too much. PLA will also wear slightly better.  
Tap the center nut for 5/16th's and the 4 bolt holes for M4. Attach to the main lead screw and enjoy greatly reduced backlash and banding.

Replaces butterfly nuts under the bed of CTC 3D Printers

These make level adjustments to the printing bed much easier and quicker.
4 of these are needed.

I found:
1) better results with ABS.
2) Print thumb wheel down
3) With supports. to make supports easier to remove I found that the following settings worked best:
....... Supports need to run across the face of the nut opening, not into the nut opening
...... Support to model Spacing 1.0mm
........Margin 0.5mm
........Density 0.25
4) Clean out the nut opening with a blade and the centre hole with a drill bit
5) Insert one of the "spare" nuts in the slot
6) Remove the thumbscrews evenly to avoid undue stress to the heater bed
7) Replace with new thumb screws

description.text: 3D printable whistles. Prints mostly without support.

Whistles I made for my daughters, currently they work for me, but the girls cannot get enough air through them to make them work.

The peas do not work as intended so I broke them out of my first print, and will remove them from future versions. I will be tweaking these so that my daughters can use them. It is interesting to hear the difference in tone that the added volume creates.

Print these 'top down' so that the only support required is through the mouthpiece.

The Whistle03_50pc is the same as Whistle02, only scaled to 50% of the original size. This one my daughters can use, however the tone is quite ear piercing.

The tube whistles are tricky, I am working on a way to get these to work consistently while printing vertically. I have added a tongue, although this still does not get a good tone working. If you 'plug' the end with your finger while blowing you can get a mediocre tone. More updates coming soon.
